        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our primary goal is to resolve the inner edge of the debris disk.  Because tau Ceti is a nearby star, the disk is relatively large on the sky. The inner edge is predicted to be 8-10 AU (i.e. 2.2”-2.8”) from the star. To cover the possible range of inner edges, we require coverage extending to a potential radius of 20 AU from the star, which requires a field of view of 11 arcsec. This will include the entire disk as resolved by Herschel.  

We therefore propose to use band 6 rather than band 7, because of the better sensitivity and larger field of view.

The star, at 0.44 mJy, will be detected, allowing us to look for offsets in the disk caused by an unseen planet, as well as to measure the inclination of the disk.

Because the scale of the disk is fairly large (11 arcsec) we require use of the ACA. By pushing to a sensitivity of 30 microJy per 1” beam, we can detect the predicted edge with a SNR of about 10 with a total observation+overhead+ACA time of 4 hours.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
